Havells India | 4Q a beat, but how sustainable is it?<https://jmflresearch.=
com/Download?ReportId=3D21211&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Rating Downgrade                   ADD                 INR 1,490

Havells missed 4Q revenue estimate but beat EBITDA/PAT estimates given (1) =
stronger C&W margin, and (2) lower-than-expected losses in Lloyd despite re=
venue declining 19% YoY. Within C&W, Havells reported ~6% volume growth, wi=
th wires (higher share of copper) volume declining while cables (mix of cop=
per and aluminium) volume rose minimally; increasing price trends aided mar=
gin. The company indicated demand has improved off late in Lloyd after a we=
ak start to the summer and inventory may normalise only by end-April. Furth=
er, within ECD, despite a YoY revenue decline of ~3%, commentary suggested =
no market share losses. Lastly, on margin, we note a medium-term aspiration=
 to gain 200bps. That said, we build in a conservative 100bps expansion ove=
r FY26=9629E given (1) Increased investments in A&P, brand visibility initi=
atives, and R&D, and (2) unlikelihood of C&W segment margin sustaining as t=
here were gains from rising input costs in 4Q. We cut our FY27/28E estimate=
s by ~3% and value Havells at 45x Mar=9228E EPS, arriving at a TP of INR 1,=
490, implying ~10% upside to CMP. Hence, downgrade to ADD.



SBI Life Insurance | Best bet in an uncertain demand environment<https://jm=
flresearch.com/Download?ReportId=3D21208&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Result Update              BUY                 INR 2,200

SBI Life reported Q4FY26 VNB of INR 16.3bn, +2% JMFe, -2% YoY. Individual A=
PE/total APE growth of 8%/6% YoY was below estimates, while margin surprise=
d positively though it declined 210bps YoY to 28.3%. Management had expecte=
d a 1.74% full-year impact from GST 2.0 for this year, but it was lower at =
1.50%. FY26 APE growth and margin were in line with guidance at 13%/27.5%. =
Management guided for 14% APE growth and 27=9628% VNB margin for FY27E and =
the near term. We have hardly changed our VNB estimates; we slightly cut AP=
E growth but raise margin forecasts. We maintain BUY with a revised TP of I=
NR 2,200, valuing the stock at 1.9x Mar=9228E EVPS of INR 1,158 (against 1.=
9x Mar=9228E EVPS of INR 1,135 earlier). March industry volume data and the=
se 4Q results reinforce our view that SBI Life is the best play in life ins=
urance (a defensive sector in itself) when there is demand uncertainty; it =
remains our top pick in the space.



Tech Mahindra | Inline 4Q results; FY27 margin trajectory remains on track<=
https://jmflresearch.com/Download?ReportId=3D21209&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Result Update              ADD                 INR 1,555

Tech Mahindra reported 4QFY26 results =96 revenues and margins were largely=
 inline. Revenue growth came in at 0.6% cc QoQ vs expectation of 0.4% cc Qo=
Q. EBIT margins at 13.8% =96 inline versus JMFL and consensus expectations.=
 Forward looking indicators =96 i) LTM new TCV grew ~42% YoY in FY26 versus=
 ~43% YoY new TCV growth in FY25 (LTM book to bill of 0.59x in FY26 versus =
0.43x in FY25). ii) Headcount saw a slight decline -1.3% QoQ / -0.7% YoY. i=
ii) Management commentary =96 confident of doing better than the industry g=
rowth and achieve 15% EBIT margins in FY27. Industry growth is expected to =
be 2-4% or 3-5%. Tech Mahindra has executed well on margins =96 already fac=
tored in the valuations, in our view. Valuations are at 19x FY27 consensus =
EPS, at c.7% premium to the sector. We revise our EPS estimates marginally =
over FY27-28E, incorporating 4Q results. Maintain target multiple of 19x Se=
p 27 =96 revised TP of INR 1,555 (versus INR 1,550 earlier). Maintain ADD.



Tata Communications | Earnings beat on strong digital portfolio growth<http=
s://jmflresearch.com/Download?ReportId=3D21210&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Result Update              BUY                 INR 1,980

Tata Communications (TCOM) reported consolidated revenue of INR 65.5bn (up =
5.9% QoQ and 9.4% YoY) for Q4FY26, higher than JMFe/consensus, led by stron=
g growth across digital portfolio, core connectivity, voice segments and TC=
R. Data segment revenue was 4.2% higher than JMFe at INR 56.8bn (up 6.1% Qo=
Q and 11.5% YoY) as digital portfolio revenue was 6.7% higher than JMFe at =
INR 29.1bn (up 9.4% QoQ and 19.2% YoY) and core connectivity revenue was al=
so 1.7% higher at INR 27.7bn (up 2.8% QoQ and 4.5% YoY). However, consolida=
ted EBITDA, at INR 12.8bn (up 4.5% QoQ and 14.4% YoY), was only 0.9-2.6% hi=
gher than JMFe/consensus due to higher network and other opex, resulting in=
 EBITDA margin of 19.6% in Q4FY26 (19.8% in 3QFY26). Net debt fell QoQ to I=
NR 94bn while capex fell QoQ to INR 5.4bn or 8.3% of revenue in 4Q. We main=
tain our BUY rating on TCOM (unchanged TP of INR 1,980/share) based on 10x =
FY28 EV/EBITDA multiple for the data segment (5Y historical average of 11x)=
 as we expect data segment EBITDA to grow at a robust CAGR of ~20% over FY2=
6=9629E, driven by a) strong growth in digital portfolio, positioned strong=
ly across key megatrends like cloud, AI, IoT, etc.; b) improvement in overa=
ll EBITDA margin from current ~20% to ~22% by FY28 (management guidance of =
23=9625%) as operating leverage and acquisition synergies are likely to be =
partly offset by adverse revenue mix.



Sunteck Realty | Strong pre-sales with improving collections<https://jmflre=
search.com/Download?ReportId=3D21207&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Result Update              BUY                 INR 560

Sunteck Realty (SRL) posted robust FY26 pre-sales of c. INR 31.6bn (+25% Yo=
Y) with Q4FY26 at c. INR 10.6bn (+22% YoY; +45% QoQ; -4% JMFe), underpinned=
 by sustained traction in premium and uber-luxury segments. Quarterly colle=
ctions increased 39% YoY to c. INR 4.3bn; for FY26, collections rose 14% Yo=
Y to INR 14.3bn with an operating surplus of INR 5.5bn (+48% YoY). Collecti=
ons are set to improve meaningfully over FY27/FY28 as execution picks up pa=
ce. Business development accelerated during the year with investments in la=
nd increasing to c. INR 8bn (from c. INR 1.8bn in FY25) and the addition of=
 c. INR 50bn GDV across three new projects, with embedded margins of c. 30=
=9635%. The launch pipeline remains healthy (c. INR 70bn GDV for FY27), inc=
luding subsequent phases at Vasai and Naigaon alongside a recently signed J=
DA project in Mira Road. The Dubai project is launch-ready, subject to geop=
olitical normalisation. Overall, management expresses confidence in sustain=
ing current pre-sales momentum into FY27, irrespective of the Dubai project=
 launch. Pre-sales could expand at 27% CAGR over FY26=9628E on the back of =
multiple launches. We reiterate BUY with a DCF based Mar=9227E TP of INR 56=
0.



PNC Infratech | Receives much awaited NHAI orders; backlog strengthens<http=
s://jmflresearch.com/Download?ReportId=3D21204&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Company Update                     BUY                 INR 345

PNC Infratech (PNC) has been declared L1 by the NHAI in two HAM road projec=
ts for 4-laning of the Barabanki=96Biswariya stretch in Uttar Pradesh; this=
 would have a total EPC value of c. INR 30bn. And given the packages are co=
ntiguous, we expect them to support margins. These wins are particularly po=
sitive as NHAI order inflows had remained slow over the past two years=97 f=
or instance, PNC=92s FY26 inflows aggregated INR 60bn versus guidance of IN=
R 120bn. Now these fresh wins will strengthen order backlog and improve exe=
cution visibility. Order backlog stood at a strong INR 203bn (2.9x TTM reve=
nue) at end-Dec-25. All in all, we reckon a robust EPS CAGR of 22% over FY2=
5=9628E. Meanwhile, the stock is trading at an attractive 10x/8x FY27E/28E =
EPS. All in all, our valuation and TP remain unchanged=97we value the EPC b=
usiness at 13x FY27E EPS yielding an SotP-based TP of INR 345; maintain BUY=
.



ABB India | Parent reported order inflows, which seems largely inline<https=
://jmflresearch.com/Download?ReportId=3D21206&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Flash Update

ABB India=92s parent entity ABB Global has reported 1QCY26 numbers with ove=
rall 24% YoY growth in order inflows on a comparable basis (possibly adjust=
ing for sale of Robotics & Automation). A positive read-through for India i=
s the reported 1QCY26 order inflow of +26% YoY, the highest in the key AMEA=
 region for ABB Global. This appears in-line with our estimate of INR43bn (=
preview note) of ~27% YoY order inflow (ex. Robotics) for ABB India in 1QCY=
26E. That said, margins may remain under pressure for ABB India. Moreover, =
current valuations make the risk reward profile significantly adverse, in o=
ur view.



Strategy | JM India Pulse =96 Mar=9226<https://jmflresearch.com/Download?Re=
portId=3D21205&DownloadType=3Dshow>

Sector Update

In this note, we lay out the most important monthly market, sectoral and ec=
onomic indicators tracked by the JM Financial research team. The indicators=
 span high-frequency macro variables and sector-level operating metrics tha=
t help assess near-term growth momentum and emerging inflection points. Esc=
alation in the West Asia conflict sent Brent crude oil price soaring past t=
he USD 100/bbl mark. FII selling intensified and the INR weakened; however,=
 the trade deficit narrowed in Mar=9226. The domestic environment reflects =
selective strength led by improving discretionary consumption and credit gr=
owth amid easing financial conditions. Household financialisation remains r=
esilient even as digital payment growth normalises. Industrial activity mod=
erated slightly with capex remaining uneven. Rising oil and gas prices, sup=
ply disruptions and geopolitical uncertainty have driven the recent volatil=
ity in Indian equity markets, though peace talks between the US and Iran ha=
ve improved market sentiment.


